<br>
The reason I bring this up is that it reminds me of conversations I have had with classmates and, to some extent, my girlfriend, where they don't seem to realize that some people (including them) do grow up privileged in this country and have had opportunities where they may not have otherwise had those opportunities.  There have been a few posts where people have mentioned how they have been able to work their way out of a bad situation and kudos to them.  Just realize that not everyone in that situation is able to do so and we should have compassion for folks with fewer opportunities (for instance, disabilities that prohibit them from working).  <br>
<br>
I read a report recently about upward mobility in this country.  While opportunities abound, the fact remains that folks that are born into wealthy backgrounds are very likely to be wealthy themselves and to earn high incomes.  Conversely, folks with low-income parents are likely to earn low incomes as well.  That isn't a huge coincidence.  In order to make it in this country, you need opportunity and desire.  Folks raised in upper-income families are presented with more opportunities.<br>
<br>
I love this country because it does, more than any other country in my opinion, provide opportunities for people to better themselves.  It is heartening to read success stories.  We need to remember though that some folks lack the abilities to get themselves out of situations and we shouldn't judge them for that.<br>
<br>
Trakon Mistrunner<br>
Level 54 Iksar Monk<br>
